    "Then we first observe that for any Y ∈ (A u) b:■ • i Y = {ξ(■ A i y) | y ∈ A and Y ≤ ξ(y)} by (5.13) = {↓ Au ■ A i y | y ∈ A and Y ⊆ ↓ Au y} by definition of (A u) b and ξ = {x ∈ A u | ∀y ∈ A: if Y ⊆ ↓ Au y, then x ⊑ ■ A i y} by definition of ↓ Au = {x ∈ A u | ∀y ∈ A: if Y ⊆ ↓ Au y, then x ∈ ■ (Au) b i ↓ Au y} ⊇ ■ (Au) b i Y,where the last equation holds by the equivalence of x ⊑ ■ A i y and x ∈ ■ (Au) b i ↓ Au y already proved for Theorem 5.17.5, and the ⊇ inclusion holds becauseY ⊆ ↓ Au y implies ■ (Au) b i Y ⊆ ■ (Au) b i ↓ Au y.",
    "In the other direction, suppose x ̸ ∈ ■ (Au) b i Y, so ∃z: xR Au i z and z ̸ ∈ Y.",
    "Since z ̸ ∈ Y, it follows by refinability for Y that ∃z ′ ⊑ z ∀z ′′ ⊑ z ′, z ′′ ̸ ∈ Y.",
    "Then by persistence for Y, it follows that for all y ∈ Y, y ∧ z ′ ̸ ∈ Y, so y ∧ z ′ = ⊥, so y ⊑ -z ′.",
    "Thus, Y ⊆ ↓ Au -z ′."
